INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a99aa0ed-7b1a-404f-8aef-af244b24acba',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jenkins Shared Libraries — Reuse Pipeline Logic Across Every Repo$escape$,
  $escape$When you find yourself copy-pasting the same Jenkinsfile stages across dozens of repos, Jenkins Shared Libraries are the fix. Define a library in a Git repo with the standard layout: `vars/` for global call steps, `src/` for Groovy classes, and `resources/` for static files. Register it in Manage Jenkins → Configure System → Global Pipeline Libraries, then consume it with `@Library('my-lib@main') _` at the top of any Jenkinsfile.

Steps defined in `vars/buildAndPush.groovy` become first-class pipeline steps — call them like `buildAndPush(image: 'myapp', tag: env.GIT_COMMIT)`. Use `src/org/myorg/Docker.groovy` for complex logic that benefits from a proper class structure with CPS-safe methods.

Agent config belongs in the library too. Define a `podTemplate` wrapper in `vars/k8sAgent.groovy` so every team gets the same Kubernetes agent spec without duplicating YAML. Pair this with `Jenkinsfile` containing only business logic — the library owns the how, the repo owns the what.$escape$,
  $escape$// vars/buildAndPush.groovy
def call(Map config) {
    def image = config.image
    def tag   = config.tag ?: env.BUILD_NUMBER

    docker.withRegistry('https://registry.example.com', 'registry-creds') {
        def built = docker.build("${image}:${tag}")
        built.push()
        built.push('latest')
    }
}

// Jenkinsfile in any repo
@Library('my-lib@main') _

pipeline {
    agent { label 'docker-agent' }
    stages {
        stage('Build & Push') {
            steps { buildAndPush(image: 'myapp', tag: env.GIT_COMMIT) }
        }
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
