INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '08c9e25c-7008-4442-882e-f293008a35da',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jenkins Caching — Dependency Caching, Docker Layer Caching, and Cache Invalidation$escape$,
  $escape$Jenkins has no built-in caching layer — you implement it explicitly. For Maven/Gradle, mount the local repo as a volume or use the `stash`/`unstash` steps to persist `.m2` or `.gradle` across stages. Better: share a host-level cache directory via `ws()` or a persistent agent volume, so all builds on that node reuse downloaded artifacts without re-fetching from Artifactory.

For Docker builds, enable BuildKit with `DOCKER_BUILDKIT=1` and ensure your `Dockerfile` orders layers from least- to most-frequently changed — base image, system deps, then app code. On the same agent, the layer cache is on-disk automatically. For distributed agents or ephemeral cloud agents, push intermediate layers to a registry using `--cache-from` and `--cache-to` with `registry` mode.

Cache invalidation is the hard part. Tie cache keys to lockfile hashes: compute `sha256sum package-lock.json` and use that as a directory name under your cache root. When the lockfile changes, the path misses and a fresh install runs. Stale caches cause silent failures — add a `post { always { cleanWs() } }` on the branch that owns the cache volume, scheduled weekly.$escape$,
  $escape$pipeline {
  agent any
  environment {
    DOCKER_BUILDKIT = '1'
    CACHE_KEY = sh(script: 'sha256sum package-lock.json | cut -d" " -f1', returnStdout: true).trim()
  }
  stages {
    stage('Restore deps') {
      steps {
        sh 'cp -r /cache/node_modules/${CACHE_KEY}/node_modules . 2>/dev/null || npm ci && mkdir -p /cache/node_modules/${CACHE_KEY} && cp -r node_modules /cache/node_modules/${CACHE_KEY}/'
      }
    }
    stage('Docker Build') {
      steps {
        sh '''
          docker build \
            --cache-from registry.example.com/myapp:cache \
            --build-arg BUILDKIT_INLINE_CACHE=1 \
            -t registry.example.com/myapp:${BUILD_NUMBER} \
            -t registry.example.com/myapp:cache .
          docker push registry.example.com/myapp:cache
        '''
      }
    }
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
