INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '68c12f17-607a-4afb-adee-eac238ad940b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jenkins Pipelines — Automated Rollback on Failed Deploy Using previousSuccessfulBuild$escape$,
  $escape$Jenkins' Declarative Pipeline `post { failure { } }` block is the natural hook for automated rollback. Instead of hardcoding a version, use `currentBuild.previousSuccessfulBuild?.number` — a Groovy property on Jenkins' `RunWrapper` object — to dynamically target the last known-good artifact.

The pattern pairs cleanly with an image-tag-as-build-number convention: on failure, re-issue the `kubectl set image` command pointing at the previous build's tag. For non-Kubernetes targets, the **Copy Artifact** plugin's `lastSuccessful()` selector does the same job for WAR/JAR artifacts.

Jenkins-specific gotchas to handle:
- `previousSuccessfulBuild` is `null` on the first ever pipeline run — always guard with the safe-navigation operator `?.` or the rollback step itself will throw.
- `post { failure }` fires once after the whole pipeline fails, not per-stage — for stage-level rollback, wrap each `stage` in a `catchError` block instead.
- Annotate the build with `currentBuild.description = "ROLLED BACK to #${lastGood}"` so the Jenkins UI and audit logs make the rollback visible without digging through console output.$escape$,
  $escape$pipeline {
  agent any
  environment { IMAGE = 'myrepo/app' }
  stages {
    stage('Deploy') {
      steps {
        sh "kubectl set image deployment/app app=${IMAGE}:${BUILD_NUMBER} --record"
        sh "kubectl rollout status deployment/app --timeout=120s"
      }
    }
  }
  post {
    failure {
      script {
        def lastGood = currentBuild.previousSuccessfulBuild?.number
        if (lastGood) {
          sh "kubectl set image deployment/app app=${IMAGE}:${lastGood}"
          currentBuild.description = "ROLLED BACK to build #${lastGood}"
        } else {
          echo 'No previous successful build found — manual intervention required.'
        }
      }
    }
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
