INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '75772777-668e-4dd3-8557-1eeb0c8713bf',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jenkins GitOps — Git as the Single Source of Truth for Kubernetes Deployments$escape$,
  $escape$GitOps flips the traditional Jenkins deploy model: instead of pushing artifacts and running imperative kubectl commands, your Kubernetes manifests live in git and Jenkins reconciles cluster state to match. The Jenkinsfile itself is the IaC — checked in, reviewed via PRs, fully auditable.

The `changeset` condition gates the deploy stage so only commits touching `k8s/**` trigger a reconciliation. `kubectl apply --server-side` uses Server-Side Apply, which tracks field ownership and surfaces conflicts that client-side apply silently ignores. Adding `--prune -l app=myservice` enforces the declarative contract: resources deleted from git are deleted from the cluster. No manual cleanup, no drift.

For webhook-driven GitOps (preferred over polling), configure a GitHub webhook to POST to `<jenkins-url>/github-webhook/` and replace `pollSCM` with an empty `triggers {}` block — Jenkins reacts instantly to push events instead of lagging up to 2 minutes.

Store your kubeconfig in Jenkins Credentials as a secret file, never a plain-text string, and bind it with `withCredentials([file(...)])` so it is masked in console output and wiped from disk after the step completes.$escape$,
  $escape$pipeline {
  agent any
  triggers { pollSCM('H/2 * * * *') }
  stages {
    stage('Reconcile') {
      when { changeset 'k8s/**' }
      steps {
        withCredentials([file(credentialsId: 'kubeconfig', variable: 'KUBECONFIG')]) {
          sh 'kubectl apply --server-side -f k8s/ --prune -l app=myservice'
        }
      }
    }
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
